/*Date: 		17JAN2026*/
/*Analyst:		Beau Brouillette*/
/*Description:	The purpose of this script is to import datasets for my portfolio project on SFO Customer Sastisfaction.

				The City and County of San Francisco has made some customer survey information publically available.
				These surveys capture customer satisfaction survey responses before and after an update to the TSA
				screening area at one of the San Francisco International Airport (SFO) terminals in 2019. 
				
				Details on the source of this data are provided below:
					SFO May URL: https://data.sfgov.org/Transportation/SFO-Screening-Checkpoint-Satisfaction-May-2019/jt6x-6hpy/about_data
					SFO Oct URL: https://data.sfgov.org/Transportation/SFO-Screening-Checkpoint-Satisfaction-October-2019/xyey-v962/about_data

				The goal of this script is to import the majority of fields from the survey responses.  I'm running this code
				on the web-based demo version of SAS Studio, where importing from flat files from my local machine is difficult (unavailable?).
				
				Two longer string variables in the SFO datasets are not included here for now, Q8COUNTRY and Q3A_TEXT.
				Rationale for excluding these for now is that the highly variable length of these two text strings complicates
				the datalines import used here.  I'm interested in quickly grabbing the bulk of the data and moving on.
				As well, I will probably chose to pull the customer narrative in Q3A_TEXT into Python or another tool for 
				text analysis.  Q8COUNTRY provides additional detail for the Q8 response, 
					"Do you live in ...
						1 - The 9-county Bay Area
						2 - Northern California outside the Bay Area
						3 - Somewhere else in the United States
						4 - Another country (outside of the U.S.)
						0 - Blank "
				For now, it seems sufficient to know that the customer lives outside the United States.
				
				Note that this approach is used due to the lack of ability to import files directly using this free web-based installation of SAS Studio.
				
				Prior to copying the raw data over, I excluded the two text files above and formatted the DATE variable as DATE9 (instead of datetime with uninformative timestamp)
				I also populated null (.) for blank observations of Q4_2, Q4_3, Q3A2, and Q3A3 to address import issues identified in testing.
				*/


data RAW_MAY_DAT;
infile datalines dlm = '09'x missover; /*DLM option defines the delimiter as TAB.  MISSOVER option holds the import pointer so that it does not skip to a new record until the end of a data line.*/
input RESPNUM CCGID RUNID $ AREA $ DAY $ DATE date9. METH Q1 Q2A Q2B Q2C Q2D Q2E Q2F Q2G Q2H Q2I Q2J Q2K Q2L Q3 Q4_1 Q4_2 Q4_3 Q5 Q6 Q7 Q8 Q9 Q10 LANG Q3A1 Q3A2 Q3A3;
datalines;
